******
[1] Washington
Date: Mon 11 May 2020
Source: The Watchdog Online [abridged, edited]
http://thewatchdogonline.com/king-county-experiencing-a-dramatic-increase-in-hepatitis-a-cases-28609


In the past 4 months, King County has seen a surge in hepatitis A cases, with 71 confirmed putting the annual average of 5-16 to shame.

The Washington Department of Health had to declare a statewide hepatitis A outbreak on 30 Jul 2019. Numbers grew exponentially in the fall as more people began to show signs of the disease. Then came 2020, with 18 onsets in January, 19 in February, and a jump to 28 in March.

Similarly to the coronavirus, hepatitis A virus [HAV] thrives in poorly sanitized environments and transmits through contact with infected people and surfaces. It is a liver infection that originates from the ingestion of microscopic fecal matter of an infected person. Anyone who has not gotten a vaccine is at risk. It mostly affects the homeless and people who use street drugs, but also inmates, international travelers, people with chronic liver disease, or clotting disorders, and caregivers assisting hepatitis patients. Furthermore, it can transmit through sexual intercourse and the consumption of contaminated foods and drinks. On average, the virus incubates for 28 days, but it can take as long as 50 for its symptoms to manifest, and weeks to months for a person to recover. Hepatitis A has a mortality rate of 0.5% and does not become chronic, but its symptoms can be debilitating (or completely absent).

Between 1 Apr 2019, and 3 Jan 2020, there were 154 cases in the entire state, meaning that, during the same time, symptomatic people in King County alone represented approximately 27% of the affected population, this data is justified by the notoriously high homelessness and drug addiction rates in the county. However, April 2020 also saw a reduction of diagnosed cases, which fell to 17, while only 8 people began to show any symptoms. The decrease might be related to COVID-19 precautionary action. The fear of catching this virus could induce possible hepatitis-infected individuals to avoid hospitals and clinics, causing their illness to remain unreported and untreated. On a positive note, the drop may be the result of physical distancing, which could have contributed to limit the spread, and of the effectiveness of hepatitis A preventive programs.

In July 2019, King County Executive Dow Constantine announced he was allocating USD 350 000 from the Loss Control Program fund to extend free hepatitis A vaccinations and limit the spread among the homeless. In 2020, King County added USD 322 000 to continue the service. These vaccinations are available in various locations and mobile stations. Since January 2019, more than 2500 homeless and drug users have received immunization.

[Byline: Luisa Loi]

